:::summary
Weather is the state of the atmosphere at a given time and place — the combination of temperature, humidity, precipitation, wind, and atmospheric pressure that determines whether a day is sunny or stormy, still or turbulent. Meteorology, the science of weather, is one of the most practically important branches of earth science, drawing on physics, chemistry, mathematics, and fluid dynamics to understand and forecast the perpetual motion of Earth's atmosphere. From ancient peoples reading the sky to modern satellite networks and computer models, humanity's effort to understand and predict the weather reflects our enduring desire to comprehend the world God has made.
:::

